00:14:42.070 --> 00:14:43.590
STEVE GROVE: So Nikhyl, you
launch a product like this,

00:14:43.590 --> 00:14:46.320
you have a sense for how you
think it's going to be used.

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:48.630
And then it's out in the wild,
and people start using it.

00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:51.760
What can you tell us about how
Hangouts have been used since

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:54.280
launch that has been instructive
for you about the

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:55.060
technology?

00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:57.650
NIKHYL SINGHAL: So we launched
it almost exactly a year ago.

00:14:57.650 --> 00:15:00.790
And what attracted me to
Hangouts initially was we

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:02.450
didn't want to just do
video conferencing.

00:15:02.450 --> 00:15:04.390
I think there's a lot
of solutions out

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:07.040
there for video calling.

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:10.100
Google is very focused
on innovating here.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:13.040
And I think when you look at
social communities and

00:15:13.040 --> 00:15:14.580
real-time communication,
we're in the

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:16.160
first and second inning.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:18.200
There's lots and lots of
interesting use cases.

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:22.320
We saw Chatroulette get born
about three, four years ago.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:24.000
Clearly interesting.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:24.830
That's one way to describe it.

00:15:24.830 --> 00:15:27.490
There's been lots and lots
of other experiments.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:29.100
But no one's really
figured it out.

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:32.480
And so I think Chee had
this instinct, the

00:15:32.480 --> 00:15:33.290
team had this instinct.

00:15:33.290 --> 00:15:34.200
We launched it.

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:36.920
And within the first few months,
the stories just

00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:38.680
started to come in.

00:15:38.680 --> 00:15:42.910
Some of the most notable, I
think, there was a kid who was

00:15:42.910 --> 00:15:46.320
rushed to the emergency room
in a local hospital.

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:49.210
The doctor wasn't able to
perform the surgery.

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:54.700
And so the 15-, 16-year-old
kid was in a

00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:55.730
life threatening situation.

00:15:55.730 --> 00:15:58.760
And someone had the insight to
actually post to Google+.

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:02.870
And they were able to connect
with a doctor in a local city

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:05.710
and, actually using video, guide
him through the surgery,

00:16:05.710 --> 00:16:08.660
save the child's life.

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:12.990
Certainly something different
was going on there.

00:16:12.990 --> 00:16:16.440
In Calcutta, there is an
orphanage of hundreds and

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:19.050
hundreds of kids who don't
speak English.

00:16:19.050 --> 00:16:21.400
And the way to get out
of an orphanage is

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:22.830
largely to have language.

00:16:22.830 --> 00:16:25.540
And English is not an easy
language to pick up from an

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:27.800
orphanage, where they don't
really talk to you in English.

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:31.300
And so local university
professors volunteer their

00:16:31.300 --> 00:16:34.400
time to actually teach English
in an auditorium much like

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:37.850
this to kids using Hangouts.

00:16:37.850 --> 00:16:44.980
Probably the most memorable one
that I heard was one of

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:48.160
the father-in-laws of a Hangout
user was diagnosed

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:49.150
with Parkinson's.

00:16:49.150 --> 00:16:52.420
And he knew that his time where
he was able to speak and

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:56.460
he was able to control his
hands was limited.

00:16:56.460 --> 00:17:00.500
And so he pulled together all
of his grandkids into a

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:04.140
Hangout and taught them
how to tie a bow tie.

00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:07.944
And that way, Hangouts has
really struck a nerve, an

00:17:07.944 --> 00:17:10.589
emotional nerve and
a social nerve.

00:17:10.589 --> 00:17:13.910
And what we've done as a team is
actually we've been blessed

00:17:13.910 --> 00:17:16.040
with the community grabbing
hold and taking it so many

00:17:16.040 --> 00:17:18.430
places that we've essentially
turned into a

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:19.910
highly reactive team.

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:22.819
And of the first things we
noticed was that as soon as

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:26.349
these conversations started to
be formed, people wanted the

00:17:26.349 --> 00:17:27.700
ability to share them.

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:30.980
And the concept of sharing a
conversation isn't actually

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:33.410
possible without a product
like ours.

00:17:33.410 --> 00:17:36.310
And so initially, it was
people recording those

00:17:36.310 --> 00:17:39.320
conversations using their own
screen capture software,

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:41.710
putting them on disk, and
then uploading them.

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:43.620
But then we looked at each
other, and we said, well,

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:44.690
clearly, we're Google.

00:17:44.690 --> 00:17:48.260
YouTube is potentially the
best video distribution

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:49.760
platform in the world.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.730
Why don't we connect those
two things together?

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:55.530
And what we launched was
Hangouts on Air, which was

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:59.460
launched last winter essentially
as a way for

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:01.650
people to have a conversation
and

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:02.920
distribute it on the internet.

00:18:02.920 --> 00:18:05.840
And everyday users were able
to do that, for the first

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:08.780
time, get a stage where they
can actually have a public

00:18:08.780 --> 00:18:09.800
conversation.

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.700
But then the media grabbed it.

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:15.500
Because they wanted to find
conversations, elicit

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:18.380
conversation, and create
new conversations.

00:18:18.380 --> 00:18:20.720
And I think that maybe the
mantra that we've started to

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:23.910
think about is Hangouts are a
great tool to connect you with

00:18:23.910 --> 00:18:26.570
people that you know you want
to have a conversation with.

00:18:26.570 --> 00:18:30.090
But also, our goal is to find
conversations you didn't think

00:18:30.090 --> 00:18:31.600
you wanted to have.

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:33.655
And I think that's what's really
magical about what

00:18:33.655 --> 00:18:34.815
we've seen so far.

00:18:34.815 --> 00:18:36.500
STEVE GROVE: Discovering these
conversations that you

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:38.600
wouldn't have otherwise
had access to.

00:18:38.600 --> 00:18:39.820
NIKHYL SINGHAL: Absolutely.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:42.120
STEVE GROVE: Since we've started
and seen media using

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:43.250
Hangouts more and more, you
and I have had a chance to

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:45.400
