Tell our friends here a little
bit about what you've heard

00:18:48.590 --> 00:18:51.680
from the media and other
partners who clearly have

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:54.200
video technology to create
conversations, but are really

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:57.260
grabbing onto Hangouts as a
way to engage audiences.

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:58.785
NIKHYL SINGHAL: So there's two
things that we continue to

00:18:58.785 --> 00:19:01.020
hear, and they have a
lot to do with the

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:02.030
two things I mentioned.

00:19:02.030 --> 00:19:06.710
One is people look at Hangouts
as a way to minimize the

00:19:06.710 --> 00:19:07.830
satellite truck.

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:09.760
So it's a satellite truck
in your pocket

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:11.200
for the first time.

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:14.440
And so as a team, we've been
developing technology to

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:17.550
improve the quality of the
video, to think about vetting.

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:20.650
So how do I make sure that
the participants and the

00:19:20.650 --> 00:19:22.410
conversation is curated?

00:19:22.410 --> 00:19:24.640
How do I make sure that the
conversation's interactive?

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:26.980
And I think we're going to show
some things about that.

00:19:26.980 --> 00:19:31.610
And so they look at it as a
replacement for being able to

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:34.650
pull together what they usually
do with studios, and

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:37.040
cameras, and very
expensive gear.

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:38.140
That's one side.

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:42.130
But then you have a situation
like what Sarah Hill did.

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:46.590
She's a very talented
broadcaster that is at a local

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:47.830
