Make them better by making them
more collaborative and

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:48.800
more real-time.

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:52.630
And the whole platform effort we
had around that is just to

00:21:52.630 --> 00:21:57.780
really facilitate new
experiences and new ideas and

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:01.780
to allow developers to really
enhance their applications.

00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:05.880
The biggest takeaway I have
around the whole platform is

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:10.470
that we tried to make the
Hangout API platform really

00:22:10.470 --> 00:22:14.120
simple and built upon the notion
that anything that you

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:17.420
can do in your app already on
the web, you can keep it and

00:22:17.420 --> 00:22:19.640
just add Hangouts to it.

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:20.750
You don't have to redesign it.

00:22:20.750 --> 00:22:21.880
You don't have to
re-architect it.

00:22:21.880 --> 00:22:24.480
It is just adding.

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:27.460
You can take your app and iFrame
it into a Hangout, and

00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:30.290
then add the multi-person and
the video capabilities onto

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:31.920
it, and extend it.

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:34.170
We did a session just now
just prior to this one.

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:36.890
And we have a code lab
at 4 o'clock today.

00:22:36.890 --> 00:22:38.920
We can help people
go through that.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:41.380
And then the other thing I'd
have you all developers

00:22:41.380 --> 00:22:45.100
understand for us from this
point, especially here, but

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:50.640
ongoing, is our approach to the
platform is really to find

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:54.380
out what people are trying
to do and enable that.

00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:57.070
So the feedback that you give
us on, hey, I'm trying to do

00:22:57.070 --> 00:23:02.130
X, Y, or Z thing really helps
us plan and provide what

00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:02.710
people need.

00:23:02.710 --> 00:23:05.810
So that feedback loop here
today, but also just online,

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:08.450
ongoing is incredibly
valuable to us.

00:23:08.450 --> 00:23:10.320
STEVE GROVE: So I pulled up
an unofficial site called

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:12.780
thehangoutapps.com that has a
bunch of these Hangout apps

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:13.770
listed there.

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:15.930
It's a good start for
inspiration for people

00:23:15.930 --> 00:23:19.170
thinking about what types
of apps to develop.

00:23:19.170 --> 00:23:21.590
What can you say about the
social dynamics of

00:23:21.590 --> 00:23:24.820
multi-person video chat that a
developer can say, OK, well,

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:28.640
that's the kind of situation in
which a Hangout makes sense

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:29.550
around an application.

00:23:29.550 --> 00:23:31.630
Do you have some
insight there?

00:23:31.630 --> 00:23:35.330
CHEE CHEW: Well, whenever you
have an app where multiple

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:40.170
people are collaborating or
contributing to and sometimes

00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:42.550
it's asynchronous, where one
person goes in, and another

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:44.050
person comes in later.

00:23:44.050 --> 00:23:45.810
But once in a while,
they come in.

00:23:45.810 --> 00:23:48.320
And they start using it, and
modifying it, and contributing

00:23:48.320 --> 00:23:49.430
at the same time.

00:23:49.430 --> 00:23:54.260
That sort of flow is a great
candidate for a Hangout.

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:59.610
And allowing people to work on
things asynchronously and also

00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:03.240
make it come alive when it's in
a Hangout and then continue

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:03.950
afterwards.

00:24:03.950 --> 00:24:07.190
I think from existing apps and
productivity apps, I think

00:24:07.190 --> 00:24:08.750
that's really, really
important.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:12.440
The dynamic for a fun
entertainment app inside a

00:24:12.440 --> 00:24:14.260
Hangout, I think that there are
a couple of things that

00:24:14.260 --> 00:24:15.800
you really have to
think about.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:19.180
One is oftentimes people are
shooting the breeze, or

00:24:19.180 --> 00:24:21.120
hanging around, and
doing whatever.

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:25.430
And then someone will
start using an app.

00:24:25.430 --> 00:24:28.690
And then it will be fun, and it
will spread throughout the

00:24:28.690 --> 00:24:30.540
rest of that Hangout app.

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:34.760
So a great Hangout app allows
for just 1 or 2

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:35.430
people to use it.

00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:38.360
Even in a group of 10, 1 or 2
people to start to use it and

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:41.690
get some value out of it, and
then have other people see it

00:24:41.690 --> 00:24:43.970
and virally get that.

00:24:43.970 --> 00:24:45.530
It also allows people
to come and go.

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:47.040
Because in a Hangout,
someone can leave,

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:48.490
or someone can join.

00:24:48.490 --> 00:24:51.960
So it allows a free flow of
people coming in and out.

00:24:51.960 --> 00:24:54.760
If you think about the dynamics
of that-- which

00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:56.150
happens in real life as well.

00:24:56.150 --> 00:24:58.715
Two people start playing cards,
someone joins, and then

00:24:58.715 --> 00:25:00.310
someone else comes in later.

00:25:00.310 --> 00:25:01.810
Think about those dynamics.

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:04.520
I think facilitating what really
happens in real life.

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.132
That's what you want to think
about when you build apps.

00:25:06.132 --> 00:25:09.680
STEVE GROVE: Yeah, I think the
online poker app is one of

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.640
those really natural use cases
for people coming together.

00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:12.910
CHEE CHEW: Absolutely.

00:25:12.910 --> 00:25:15.500
NIKHYL SINGHAL: It's probably
worth pointing out that

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:19.400
there's two styles of apps
that we've been seeing.

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:24.250
I think one are the YouTube,
poker, kind of mainstream

00:25:24.250 --> 00:25:26.640
activities that if you take a
group of people and you're

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:29.730
essentially in a room, what
could you give them to keep

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:31.870
them busy, to keep
them occupied.

00:25:31.870 --> 00:25:35.070
The most successful app that
actually we have is our Google

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:36.080
Effects app.

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:40.800
And we're seeing a lot of
developers build almost tools

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:43.340
or enhancements to the
video conversation.

00:25:43.340 --> 00:25:45.480
And these, if you look at a
Hangout, are the ones that

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:47.030
show up on the left side.

00:25:47.030 --> 00:25:50.285
They're not designed to be a
service or an activity in and

00:25:50.285 --> 00:25:51.280
of themselves.

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:53.020
They're actually designed to
say, well, if you're in a

00:25:53.020 --> 00:25:56.310
conversation, what could we do
with the audio, the video, or

00:25:56.310 --> 00:25:58.970
the management of the
conversation that would really

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:00.820
make the conversation
more effective?

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:03.720
And I think that both are going
to be interesting areas

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:06.270
of exploration as we start to
see developers roll those out.

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:08.980
CHEE CHEW: Those extensions that
extend and enhance the

00:26:08.980 --> 00:26:12.110
existing conversation, I think,
are ones that you don't

00:26:12.110 --> 00:26:14.040
need to get the consensus
of other people.

00:26:14.040 --> 00:26:15.820
Any one person can add value.

00:26:15.820 --> 00:26:17.720
And everyone sees what's
happening and is like, oh, how

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:18.980
do I do that?

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:21.380
Like the Lower Third app or
the Comment Tracker app.

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:24.480
There are a bunch of things like
that which really do well

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:25.200
in that sort of forum.

