frustrated because they want a
turn to talk, and all that

00:43:59.294 --> 00:43:59.720
sort of stuff.

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:03.470
And when we were using it
ourselves at 15, it wasn't a

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:04.990
great conversation.

00:44:04.990 --> 00:44:06.820
So it's a social
sort of thing.

00:44:06.820 --> 00:44:07.800
STEVE GROVE: It's not
a technical limit.

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:08.470
It's simply--

00:44:08.470 --> 00:44:14.220
CHEE CHEW: Well, we had a bug
that accidentally came out a

00:44:14.220 --> 00:44:18.405
few months ago where we pushed
the server to where the cap

00:44:18.405 --> 00:44:20.010
was removed.

00:44:20.010 --> 00:44:23.360
And we had a 40% Hangout
out in the public.

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:27.640
And people got to experience
that the technology could hold

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:29.390
up to a pretty large number.

00:44:29.390 --> 00:44:31.426
But the conversation just
couldn't handle--

00:44:31.426 --> 00:44:33.300
STEVE GROVE: A shouting match.

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:35.340
CHEE CHEW: Everyone would try
to speak, and it was like

00:44:35.340 --> 00:44:36.780
stepping on each other's toes.

00:44:36.780 --> 00:44:38.860
It wasn't a healthy
conversation.

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:43.890
Now at the same time, if you
have a room of 10-- and let's

00:44:43.890 --> 00:44:45.740
say our limit was 20--

00:44:45.740 --> 00:44:49.030
and your buddy wants to come in,
you're not really going to

00:44:49.030 --> 00:44:49.690
tell him, no.

00:44:49.690 --> 00:44:51.550
So you're going to allow
it to go to 11.

00:44:51.550 --> 00:44:53.010
And then another friend
comes and says, oh,

00:44:53.010 --> 00:44:53.970
hey, let me in there.

00:44:53.970 --> 00:44:55.880
And so you're going to
allow it to go to 12.

00:44:55.880 --> 00:44:58.760
And then another person comes in
who wants to get in there,

00:44:58.760 --> 00:45:02.100
and you're going to allow
it to go to 15 and 20.

00:45:02.100 --> 00:45:04.740
You're not going to say, no to
your friends, say, oh, hey, we

00:45:04.740 --> 00:45:07.860
have 10 right now, and that's
a little bit too many, so

00:45:07.860 --> 00:45:09.110
please don't come in.

00:45:09.110 --> 00:45:11.443
So essentially, we'll
help you by--

00:45:11.443 --> 00:45:14.432
STEVE GROVE: Good fences
make good neighbors.

00:45:14.432 --> 00:45:16.510
NIKHYL SINGHAL: I think that
part of the reason why we did

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:19.880
Hangouts on Air was also to
recognize that when you're in

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:23.510
that mode, where you are hosted,
is to allow people to

00:45:23.510 --> 00:45:24.726
actually participate in
the conversation.

00:45:24.726 --> 00:45:26.660
STEVE GROVE: You look at
broadcasters using Hangouts,

00:45:26.660 --> 00:45:29.800
and it's rare that a broadcaster
like CNN or ABC

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:30.970
will actually have 10 people.

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:33.280
Usually it's 3 to 6.

00:45:33.280 --> 00:45:35.300
Because even beyond that, if
you're trying to broadcast a

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:39.430
conversation that flows with
some kind of regularity, it,

00:45:39.430 --> 00:45:41.410
in some ways, mirrors the
talking head format of cable

00:45:41.410 --> 00:45:41.780
television.

00:45:41.780 --> 00:45:44.470
When you're watching Fox or
MSNBC, there's never much more

00:45:44.470 --> 00:45:46.160
than three or four blocks
on the screen.

00:45:46.160 --> 00:45:48.700
There's too much to handle for
an audience once you get past

00:45:48.700 --> 00:45:49.620
that limit.

00:45:49.620 --> 00:45:51.010
Let's go over here.

00:45:51.010 --> 00:45:51.660
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Colin Jones.

